'''John III Crispo''' ({{lang-it|Giovanni III Crispo}}) was the eighteenth [[Duke of the Archipelago]], ruling from 1480 when he succeeded his brother, [[Giacomo III Crispo]] (r. 1463-1480).{{sfn|Frazee|Frazee|1988|p=78}} 

Shortly after this, he reincorporated [[Santorini]], which had been ruled by [[Domenico Pisani]], husband of his niece [[Fiorenza Crispo]], into the Duchy.{{sfn|Frazee|Frazee|1988|pp=78, 95}} His raising of taxes made him very unpopular among the Greek population of [[Naxos]], however. They rebelled under their own magnates (''archontes''), and the Crispi and the other Catholic families loyal to them were shut in the island's citadel (Kastro) and were besieged by the rebels. Only the timely arrival of [[galley]]s from the [[Knights Hospitaller]] of [[Rhodes]] rescued Crispo and put an end to the revolt.{{sfn|Frazee|Frazee|1988|p=78}}

The discontent did not subside, however, and in 1494 John was killed, apparently by poison, by the locals, who sent an embassy to [[Venice]] requesting for the [[Republic of Venice|Republic]] to assume control of the island, as John's sole heir, his son [[Francesco III Crispo]], was underage.{{sfn|Frazee|Frazee|1988|p=78}} In the end, Francesco assumed his father's position in 1500.

